                            <h2 style="color: #fcc454;">Low-Carb Diet</h2>
                            <p>
                                A low-carb diet is a diet that limits the intake of carbohydrates, typically to less than 130 grams per day, although some people may consume even fewer carbs. By reducing carbs, the body is encouraged to burn stored fat for energy, leading to weight loss and other health benefits.

                                A low-carb diet usually includes foods such as meats, fish, eggs, non-starchy vegetables, nuts, and seeds, while limiting or avoiding high-carb foods such as bread, pasta, rice, and sugary snacks. Some versions of the low-carb diet, such as the ketogenic diet, are very low in carbohydrates and very high in fat.

                                Studies have shown that low-carb diets can be effective for weight loss, reducing blood sugar levels, and improving cardiovascular health. However, as with any diet, it is important to consult with a healthcare professional before starting a low-carb diet to ensure it is safe and appropriate for your individual needs and health status.
